text: I Unit Test Machine Learning 1. What is Artificial Intelligence (AI)? 1. Definition (short): AI is the field of computer science that builds systems able to perform tasks that normally require human intelligence. 2. Key idea: Make machines sense, reason, learn, and act to achieve goals. 3. Examples: Speech assistants (Siri), image recognition, chess engines, recommendation systems. 2. General AI vs Narrow AI (stepwise) 1. Narrow AI (Weak AI): a. Designed for a single task or a narrow set of tasks. b. Examples: Face recognition, spam filters, language translators. c. Current real-world AI is mostly narrow AI. 2. General AI (Strong AI / AGI): a. Hypothetical systems with human-like general intelligence across many tasks and domains. b. Can reason, plan, learn, and apply knowledge flexibly. c. Not achieved yet — still a research/vision goal. 3. Quick contrast (memorize): a. Scope: Narrow (specific) vs General (broad). b. Existence now: Narrow = Yes, General = No (so far). 3. Applications of AI (by domain — short examples) 1. Healthcare: Medical imaging diagnosis, drug discovery, patient triage chatbots. 2. Finance: Fraud detection, algorithmic trading, credit scoring. 3. Retail & E-commerce: Personalised recommendations, inventory forecasting, chatbots. 4. Transportation: Self-driving systems, route optimization, predictive maintenance. 5. Manufacturing: Robotics, quality inspection, predictive maintenance. 6. Entertainment & Media: Recommendation engines, content generation, game AI. 7. Education: Adaptive learning platforms, automated grading. 8. Customer Service: Virtual agents, sentiment analysis. (When asked in an exam, give 3–4 domains + 1 concrete example each. ) 4. History of AI & Machine Learning — timeline (compact, memorable milestones) 1. 1950s a. Alan Turing proposes the Turing Test (1950). b. Term “Artificial Intelligence” coined (Dartmouth Workshop, 1956). 2. 1960s–1970s a. Early symbolic AI and rule-based systems (expert systems beginnings). 3. 1980s a.

Tip: Link each era to a concrete tech or event — that helps retention. 5. Evolution of AI — conceptual flow 1. Symbolic AI (logic, rules) → 2. Statistical AI (probability, ML) → 3. Machine Learning (data-driven) → 4. Deep Learning (neural nets on large data) → 5. Generative & Foundation Models (large pretrained models) Remember: the trend moves from rules to data and from human- coded logic to learned representations. 7. Types of Machine Learning (stepwise) 1. Supervised Learning a. Uses labeled data (input → correct output). b. Tasks: Classification (e. g. , spam/not spam), Regression (predict price). 2. Unsupervised Learning a. Uses unlabeled data; finds structure/patterns. b. Tasks: Clustering (group customers), Dimensionality reduction (PCA). 3. Semi-supervised Learning a. Mix of labeled + large unlabeled — useful when labels are scarce. 4. Reinforcement Learning (RL) a. An agent learns via trial & error, receiving rewards/punishments. b. Example: Game playing, robotics control. 8. Relationship between AI and Machine Learning (crisp) 1. Hierarchy: AI = broad field. ML ⊂ AI (ML is one approach to achieve AI). 2.

Analogy: AI is the destination (intelligent systems); ML is one vehicle (learning from data). 3. Other AI approaches: Symbolic logic, rule-based systems, evolutionary algorithms — not all are 4. Modern trend: Most recent, successful AI systems rely heavily on ML, especially deep learning. 9. Key concepts & terms (quick flashcards) • Model: Mathematical function/process learned from data. • Feature: Measurable property (input variable). • Label/Target: The correct output used in supervised learning. • Training/Testing: Train = learn from data; Test = evaluate on unseen data. • Overfitting: Model memorizes training data, performs poorly on new data. • Underfitting: Model too simple; fails to capture patterns. • Epoch: One full pass over training data. • Loss/Cost: Measure of model error during training. • Gradient Descent: Optimization method to minimize loss. 10. Applications (4 marks): List 3 domains and a one-sentence concrete application each Overview of Machine Learning: 1. What is Machine Learning? 1. Machine Learning (ML) is a subfield of Artificial Intelligence where computers learn patterns from data instead of being explicitly programmed. 2. ML models improve automatically as they get more data and experience. 3. Typical workflow: Data → Train Model → Model learns patterns → Predict on new data One-line definition for exams: Machine Learning is the technique that enables systems to learn from data and make predictions or decisions without being explicitly programmed. 2. Why Machine Learning? Here are reasons that examiners expect: 1. Handling large & complex data a. Traditional programming fails when rules are too complex. b. ML finds patterns from massive datasets. 2. Improves performance automatically a. Models get better as more data is added. 3. Works where manual rules are impossible a. e. g. , face recognition, speech detection. 4. Better predictions & decision-making a. Used in forecasting, risk detection, medical diagnosis. 5. Automation a. Reduces human effort in repetitive or analytical tasks. Short exam answer: ML is needed because modern problems involve huge data, non-linear patterns, and complex environments where writing manual rules is not practical. 3. Broad Categories of Machine Learning Algorithms A. Supervised Learning 1. Uses labeled data → input + correct output. 2. Goal: Learn a function that maps input → output. 3. Used for prediction. Types of Supervised Learning: 1. Classification • Output is categorical (labels/classes). • Example tasks: spam detection (spam/not spam), disease prediction (yes/no), sentiment analysis. 2. Regression • Output is continuous numerical value.

Uses unlabeled data → only inputs, no correct answers. 2. Goal: Discover patterns or structures in data. Types of Unsupervised Learning: 1. Clustering • Groups data into clusters based on similarity. • Examples: customer segmentation, grouping news articles, market basket patterns. 4. Real-World Applications of Supervised & Unsupervised Learning  A. Applications of Supervised Learning Use cases where we have known outputs: 1. Email spam detection – classification 2. Credit card fraud detection – classification 3. Medical diagnosis – classification 4. Weather prediction – regression 5. Stock price forecasting – regression 6. Voice assistants (speech-to-text) – supervised classification 7. Quality inspection in factories – classification (“defect / no defect”) B. Applications of Unsupervised Learning Used for discovering hidden patterns: 1. Customer segmentation in marketing → clustering 2. Recommendation systems (group similar users/products) 3.
